## What this skill does

Drives the implementation work end-to-end for one project: walks the
user through the plan in [IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md](IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md),
applies the edits (or describes them, depending on autonomy mode),
and runs the verification recipe in [RUNBOOK.md](RUNBOOK.md).

The architectural decisions — `groupName` schema, archetype match,
data flow — are recorded in [ARCHITECTURE.md](ARCHITECTURE.md). The
capability surface the agent must support is in
[CAPABILITIES.md](CAPABILITIES.md). Don't re-derive these on every
invocation; they're the contract.

## Step 0 — autonomy

Default for this skill is **`{{AUTONOMY}}`** (inherited from the
generator). Ask the user once before doing heavy work:

> "Run end-to-end (hands-off) or check in between steps (interactive)?
> Default is {{AUTONOMY}}."

In **hands-off**: read the plan, apply each step, run verification.
Stop only on errors or hard-rule violations (see below).

In **interactive**: read the plan, present each step, **wait** for
the user to confirm before applying.

## Step 1 — read the plan

Read [IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md](IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md) and
[ARCHITECTURE.md](ARCHITECTURE.md). Confirm with the user that the
plan is current — the codebase may have moved since generation.

If the codebase has drifted (file paths in the plan don't exist; the
LLM call site moved), tell the user and offer to regenerate via
`contextual-agent-generator`.

## Step 2 — apply

{{#if MODE=="greenfield"}}
Greenfield: the scaffolds in [scaffolds/](scaffolds/) are ready to
run. Copy them into `{{PROJECT_PATH}}` (or wherever the user wants),
install deps, fill in `.env`, and run the smoke test from
`RUNBOOK.md`.
{{/if}}
{{#if MODE=="retrofit"}}
Retrofit: the plan is the file-level edit list at
[IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md](IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md). Each item is one
file edit with path, line number, and snippet. Apply in order — they
are listed in the order that minimises broken intermediate states.

Stop and ask the user **before** applying step 1 (the first edit
that touches their code) regardless of autonomy mode. After they
approve the first edit, proceed per the autonomy default.
{{/if}}

## Step 3 — verify

Run the verification recipe in [RUNBOOK.md](RUNBOOK.md). The universal
checks (API key reachable, `groupName` round-trip, end-to-end search)
are covered there along with archetype-specific verification.

Report PASS / WARN / FAIL per check. A FAIL means the agent is not
ready to ship — investigate before declaring done.

## Hard rules (inherited from the generator)

These bind every invocation of this child skill:

1. **Don't drift from the matched archetype.** If the user wants a
   different shape now, regenerate via `contextual-agent-generator`
   with the new archetype — don't bolt the new pattern onto this skill.
2. **One SDK only.** This skill scaffolds in `{{SDK}}`. If the user
   needs the other language too, regenerate.
3. **Minimum delta for retrofits.** If the change set grows past 10
   files mid-application, stop and ask. The user almost certainly
   wants a smaller scope.
4. **Never read or echo secret files.** Hard-coded across the
   scaffolds: keys come from `.env` (gitignored), never from disk
   reads of `.env.*`.
5. **Never edit `custom/`.** Anything the user has placed under
   [custom/](custom/) is theirs; preserve it across regeneration and
   don't generate competing versions of the same file.

## Regenerate

If the project has changed materially (new capabilities, new data
sources, new archetype fits better), regenerate from the parent skill:

> "Regenerate `contextual-agent-generator--{{SKILL_SUFFIX}}` — the
> agent now also needs to do X."

The parent skill's regenerate step preserves [custom/](custom/).
